                {
                    "id" : "3c510ae4-d045-4f57-8eb5-f1a7091f3d53",
                    "name": "Ramiro (+<span id=\"htdate30\"></span>)",
                    "history" : [ "<p>There is no doubt that Ramiro is the son of Ordoño. This is confirmed in the Sampiro Chronicle (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('57058ed9-8177-47fc-9bca-f96cfc2acb28'); return false;\">Santos, Francisco C. et al., <span id=\"htdate31\"></span>, pp. 53</a>; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('755c42c6-3be9-41fd-8655-22f8a6877215'); return false;\">Medieval Lands, <span id=\"htdate32\"></span></a>) and also in a document from the County of Portucalense (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('f5b801c9-ffbe-47f0-ab89-10e5ede4816d'); return false;\">Herculano, Alexandre, <span id=\"htdate33\"></span>, Diplomata et Chartae, Volumen I, Fascicvlvs I, pp. 7.</a>; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('755c42c6-3be9-41fd-8655-22f8a6877215'); return false;\">Medieval Lands, <span id=\"htdate34\"></span></a>). However, the documents diverge on the identity of his mother.</p>", "<p>When he began to rule the Kingdom of León, Ramiro ruled as Ramiro II (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('755c42c6-3be9-41fd-8655-22f8a6877215'); return false;\">Medieval Lands, <span id=\"htdate35\"></span></a>). He was responsible for expanding the kingdom's borders (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('755c42c6-3be9-41fd-8655-22f8a6877215'); return false;\">Medieval Lands, <span id=\"htdate36\"></span></a>). Among the wars he fought, the war against the Muslims is particularly notable. When we read the report of Count Don Pedro about a supposed relationship between Ramiro II and a Muslim woman named Artiga, we must highlight (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('94cddc67-cec8-414a-9885-6d3e7ee952ba'); return false;\">Nobiliário Conde Dom Pedro, <span id=\"htdate37\"></span>, pp. 4, 111 - 116</a>): <ul><li>The details of the description.</li><li>The omission of the second marriage of Ramiro II with Urraca.</li><li>The mention of Sancho as the son of Adosinda (Aldara) and not his mother Urraca.</li></ul></p>", "<p>The lack of documentation to confirm the marriage of Ramiro II has led different researchers to seek documentation that can indirectly confirm this marriage, known as the legend of Gaia (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('84d4a783-4503-4c49-8580-292835328e4e'); return false;\">Rei, Antonio, <span id=\"htdate38\"></span></a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('03f704e5-1d8d-40b4-a7b8-980bfa43a256'); return false;\">Geneall, <span id=\"htdate39\"></span></a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('9b188295-959f-42f6-ad70-40d045e3237e'); return false;\">Rodrigues de Oliveira, Natália S. T., <span id=\"htdate40\"></span></a>).</p>", "<p>What is known about the war against the Muslims is that Ramiro II won in <span id=\"htdate41\"></span>, but the following year he suffered a significant defeat, leading him to sign a neutrality agreement with the Muslims (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('755c42c6-3be9-41fd-8655-22f8a6877215'); return false;\">Medieval Lands, <span id=\"htdate42\"></span></a>).</p>", "<p>Ramiro II had documented children from two marriages. The first wife was named Adosinda (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('652569a1-a629-402f-936c-34e4ad7b098d'); return false;\">Lacarra, José M., <span id=\"htdate43\"></span>, pp. 238</a>; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('755c42c6-3be9-41fd-8655-22f8a6877215'); return false;\">Medieval Lands, <span id=\"htdate44\"></span></a>). The second wife was named Urraca, according to the Codex Roda (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('652569a1-a629-402f-936c-34e4ad7b098d'); return false;\">Lacarra, José M., <span id=\"htdate45\"></span>, pp. 236,238</a>; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('755c42c6-3be9-41fd-8655-22f8a6877215'); return false;\">Medieval Lands, <span id=\"htdate46\"></span></a>)</p>", "<p>Portuguese chronicles, centuries after the death of Ramiro II, mentioned a third hypothetical relationship with a Muslim woman named Artiga (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('533919ff-5981-4e0c-8d92-46be8057cdab'); return false;\">Herculano, Alexandre, Scriptores, <span id=\"htdate47\"></span>, pp. 180-181</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('94cddc67-cec8-414a-9885-6d3e7ee952ba'); return false;\">Nobiliário Conde Dom Pedro, <span id=\"htdate48\"></span>, pp. 4</a>). Since these chronicles were written centuries after the events, we will treat them as hypothetical.</p>" ],
