                            "history" : [ "<p>According to lineage books (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('533919ff-5981-4e0c-8d92-46be8057cdab'); return false;\">Herculano, Alexandre, Scriptores, <span id=\"htdate62\"></span>, pp. 180-181</a>  ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('94cddc67-cec8-414a-9885-6d3e7ee952ba'); return false;\">Nobiliário Conde Dom Pedro, <span id=\"htdate63\"></span>, pp. 4</a>).</p>", "<p>The association proposed by José Mattoso suggests that the legend of Gaia could be related to him, but it is important to recognize that there is no documentation proving this connection to Ramiro II (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('31f13a98-fff1-45fc-992d-adb817743e9f'); return false;\">Mattoso, José, <span id=\"htdate64\"></span>, pp. 208</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('f7a65165-8bec-41d5-8200-dc9e38f3786c'); return false;\">Mattoso, José, <span id=\"htdate65\"></span>, pp. 492 - 493</a>).</p>" ]
                        },
                        {
                            "type" : "hypothesis",
                            "id": "72ca5af9-89ec-4425-ac8f-67b875658ccd",
                            "marriage_id": "8b13ce67-cf44-4a85-97ef-aa9ad61546e3",
                            "name" : "Lovesendo Ramires",
                            "family_id": "588c52dc-7b48-490d-acb4-044f07314444",
                            "history" : [ "According to António Rei (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('84d4a783-4503-4c49-8580-292835328e4e'); return false;\">Rei, António, <span id=\"htdate66\"></span>, pp. 11</a>)." ]
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id" : "72ca5af9-89ec-4425-ac8f-67b875658ccd",
                    "name": "Lovesendo Ramires",
                    "history" : [ "There is no documentation or chronicles confirming this person. The hypothesis of his existence is raised to create a connection between King Ramiro II and his supposed grandson, Aboazar Lovesendes, who indeed existed, but is referred to as the son of Ramiro II in the legend of Gaia (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('31f13a98-fff1-45fc-992d-adb817743e9f'); return false;\">Mattoso, José, <span id=\"htdate67\"></span>, pp. 208</a>).", "<p class=\"reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Patronymics and the Facts</b><br />When we examine documents from monasteries, the children of King Ramiro do not appear with patronymics; they are identified as <i>Regis filius</i> (Santiago de Compostela) or <i>filii Regis</i>(Sahagún). The patronymic \"Lovesendes\" indicates he is a son of Lovesendo. The same rule applies to \"Ramires\", son of Ramiro. Both names fall outside the pattern applied to princes and princesses. The \"Livro Velho\" chronicles seem to understand this rule, while Don Pedro adapts his narrative to his time. Considering there are no documents to prove the relationship, and that a different pattern was used for Lovesendo Ramires compared to princes and princesses, would you still add him to your genealogical tree?</p>" ],
